        <page n="01" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.01.09.01">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Lincoln on Negro Citizenship</head>
                <origin>N.Y. Daybook</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Using a quote from the Republican Times, The N.Y. Daybook criticizes
                    Lincoln's opinion that Negroes could be citizens of the United States. The N.Y.
                    Daybook maintains the absurdity of allowing blacks the rights of citizens.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look>x</look>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Address to the People of the United States</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>An address from members of Congress appealing to the people to help ratify
                    Amendments that can solve the secession crisis.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Some Things to be Remembered</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Item accuses the Black Republicans of hypocrisy in dealing harshly with
                    secession in the South.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Later from the Pacific</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>News from the Pacific brought by a ship that arrived in New York from
                    California.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Gov. Houston's Proclamation</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Sam Houston calls the Texas Legislature into special session to deal with
                    the Indian problem.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>Governor's Message</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Speech on the financial health of the State Government and on the crisis of
                    the Federal Government, particularly with regard to the Fugitive slave law and
                    its enforcement. The Governor supports a compromise position. Article occupies
                    the remainder of page 1 and the first five columns of page 2.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Bottom illegible</pageNote>
        </page>
        <page n="02" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.01.09.02">
            <pageNote>Columns 1-5 contain the remainder of the Governor's speech.</pageNote>
