        <page n="04" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.01.09.04">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>News of the Week</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Reports that the committee of the fourteen border states adopted a plan of
                    amending the Constitution called the Crittendon Compromise. Other news items
                    from around the country are also reported.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>The President's Action</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"Mr. Buchanan has pursued a straightforward course from the beginning and
                    he will pursue it to the end. He will exercise no dangerous power not clearly
                    delegated to him, nor will he wink at any violation of the laws which he may
                    have power to punish."</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Item praises Buchanan's resolve in the Secession crisis, particularly with
                    regard to Major Anderson and Fort Sumter.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>The Present Congress</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Criticizes congressional intransigence in allowing the Union to
                    disintegrate. It is up to Congress, the Spirit claims, to give Buchanan the
                    power to coerce or recognize the seceded States.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>A Ray of Hope</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>An article in praise of the compromises proposed by Sen. Crittenden and the
                    border state committee.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>Republican Times</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Criticizes the election of Lincoln.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>5</column>
                <head>Letter from Harrisburg</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer>Republican</trailer>
                <names/>
                <summary>Letter ridicules politicians in the State Legislature.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
        <page n="05" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.01.09.05">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>What Franklin County Pays</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Enumerates the taxes paid by Franklin County to the State Treasury.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look>x</look>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Taxation</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript>
                    <p>--The following is the valuation of Real Estate in Franklin county, taxable
                        for State purposes; the assessment of tax theron for the year 1860, as fixed
                        by the Revenue Board at its last tri-ennial meeting; also the population of
                        the County, according to the Census of 1860, and the number of taxable
                        inhabitants therein for the same year:</p>
                    <table>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Valuation,</cell>
                            <cell>$11, 661, 656 00</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Assessment of Tax,</cell>
                            <cell>30, 255 83</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Population,</cell>
                            <cell>42, 243 00</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Taxables,</cell>
                            <cell>9, 816 00</cell>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                    <p>The valuation of 1859 was $13, 068, 184 and the Assessment of Tax $33, 835
                        41, being a reduction of the amount of taxation for Franklin county of $3,
                        579 58.</p>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Table provides the valuation of real estate in the county.</summary>
                <note>frbrowser/jan61.html#1.9a</note>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Population</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript>
                    <p>--According to the Census of 1850, the population of Franklin County numbered
                        39, 904, by the Census of 1860, it is set down at 42, 243, and increase of
                        2, 389 in ten years. The previous ten years, from 1840 to 1850, the increase
                        in population was, 2, 111, or 4, 450 in the last twenty years.</p>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Gives census data for Franklin county in 1860.</summary>
                <note>frbrowser/jan61.html#1.9b</note>
                <look>x</look>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>Important from Washington</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Correspondence between the President and his Cabinet regarding events in
                    Charleston.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>Infamous and Treasonable Work</head>
                <origin>Rockland Free Press and Democrat</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Alleges that the Governor of Maine contributed funds to the Underground
                    Railroad. The article refers to the harboring of runaways as treason.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
